                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d165">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00118 European War 1939/1075: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Colombia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-23T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >February 23, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>212. Your 232, February 19, 1942. While the War Department has no objection to
                    its officers’ attached to the consulates in Colombia wearing civilian dress, it
                    believes they should have with them a set of uniforms for emergency use. The War
                    Department proposes to send the uniforms to the Military Attaché in Bogotá for
                    storage. It would be left to your discretion when and if these uniforms should
                    be worn.</p>
                <p>The Department perceives no objection.</p>
                <p>Please telegraph your views.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
